---
// LeibnizLanguageFigure — the language-independence thread, made concrete.
// One meaning ("a cat is sleeping") in three languages, each marking it a
// different way (German morphology, English word order, Chinese context),
// converging on the shared content — does the model represent that, or only
// each surface? Highlighted token = where each language carries the marking.
---
<figure class="essay-fig">
  <svg viewBox="0 0 660 220" role="img" aria-label="The same meaning — a cat is sleeping — in German (Die Katze schlaeft, marked by morphology), English (The cat sleeps, by word order), and Chinese (cat-sleep, by context), converging on one shared content">
    <defs>
      <marker id="ll-arrow" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="9" refY="5" markerWidth="5.5" markerHeight="5.5" orient="auto-start-reverse">
        <path d="M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z" fill="currentColor" />
      </marker>
    </defs>

    <text class="track-lbl" x="16" y="22">one meaning · three surfaces</text>

    <!-- DE: morphology -->
    <text class="tag" x="18" y="44">DE · morphology</text>
    <rect class="box" x="16" y="50" width="252" height="34" rx="6" />
    <text class="sent" x="30" y="72">Die Katze <tspan class="mark">schläft</tspan></text>

    <!-- EN: word order -->
    <text class="tag" x="18" y="100">EN · word order</text>
    <rect class="box" x="16" y="106" width="252" height="34" rx="6" />
    <text class="sent" x="30" y="128"><tspan class="mark">The cat</tspan> sleeps</text>

    <!-- ZH: context -->
    <text class="tag" x="18" y="156">ZH · context</text>
    <rect class="box" x="16" y="162" width="252" height="34" rx="6" />
    <text class="sent" x="30" y="184"><tspan class="mark">猫睡觉</tspan> <tspan class="sent-dim">— bare</tspan></text>

    <!-- converge to the shared meaning -->
    <line class="seq" x1="268" y1="67" x2="400" y2="116" marker-end="url(#ll-arrow)" />
    <line class="seq" x1="268" y1="123" x2="400" y2="122" marker-end="url(#ll-arrow)" />
    <line class="seq" x1="268" y1="179" x2="400" y2="128" marker-end="url(#ll-arrow)" />

    <rect class="meaning-box" x="402" y="98" width="242" height="50" rx="8" />
    <text class="meaning-lbl" x="523" y="120" text-anchor="middle">a cat is sleeping</text>
    <text class="meaning-sub" x="523" y="137" text-anchor="middle">present · singular</text>
  </svg>
  <figcaption>
    The same content sits in German morphology, English word order, and Chinese context. Does the
    model represent the meaning beneath — or, as Quine suspected, only the surface of each language?
  </figcaption>
</figure>

<style>
  .essay-fig svg { color: var(--color-text-dim); max-height: 232px; }
  .box { fill: var(--color-bg); stroke: var(--color-text-dim); stroke-width: 1; }
  .meaning-box { fill: var(--color-bg); stroke: var(--color-accent); stroke-width: 1.2; }
  .tag { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 9.5px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.08em; fill: var(--color-accent); }
  .sent { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 13px; fill: var(--color-text-muted); }
  .sent-dim { fill: var(--color-text-dim); font-style: italic; }
  .mark { fill: var(--color-accent); font-weight: 600; }
  .meaning-lbl { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 12.5px; fill: var(--color-text); }
  .meaning-sub { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 9.5px; fill: var(--color-text-dim); font-style: italic; }
  .seq { stroke: var(--color-text-dim); color: var(--color-text-dim); stroke-width: 1; }
  .track-lbl { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 11px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em; fill: var(--color-text-dim); }
</style>
